I=E2=80=99ve been following Goop as it has tried to sell just about
everything=E2=80=94skincare, TV shows, vibrators, made in Italy knits, well=
ness conferences, stores, and more=E2=80=94in the 16 years since Gwyneth Pa=
ltrow hit send on that first newsletter from her London home. By many measu=
res, the lifestyle business Paltrow has built is impressive; Goop has seen =
many iterations, and her arc of personal influence, which spans four decade=
s and every diet and workout fad imaginable, is as relevant as ever. Most r=
ecently, I=E2=80=99ve learned that
Gwyneth is maybe even trying to sell Fashion Week on a Goop runway show.

=C2=A0

But somewhere along the way, Goop got a little lost. Despite its extraordin=
ary brand power, the business lacks focus and the strong executive leadersh=
ip required to become an attractive acquisition target. This year, I=E2=80=
=99ve heard that Goop is approaching about $100 million in revenue, which h=
as been more or less flat for the past four
years. It=E2=80=99s a large number, yes, but Greycroft, Felix Capital, Ligh=
tspeed, and others won=E2=80=99t see a return on their collective $140 mill=
ion investment until Goop is profitable. Or, more likely, when a C.P.G. fir=
m takes it off the market and returns their preferred investment with a nic=
e return.

=C2=A0

Enter Julia Hunter, who propelled Jenni Kayne from $3 million to more than =
$100 million in revenue during a
memorable stint as C.E.O. a few years ago. As I=E2=80=99ve previously repor=
ted, Paltrow tapped Hunter to help Goop through its awkward phase. I connec=
ted with Hunter, who spoke uncharacteristically frankly about the company=
=E2=80=99s challenges, and optimistically about its opportunities. I found =
this refreshingly honest=E2=80=94especially given how the company normally =
communicates. Our conversation has been lightly edited and condensed.

Cutting Costs
-------------

Rachel Strugatz: What was the
first thing you did when you got in there?

=C2=A0

Julia Hunter: I=E2=80=99m focusing on topline growth and reducing the size =
of the team. The company is doing very well from a revenue perspective, but=
 operating expenses have continued to grow. I know that it=E2=80=99s unpopu=
lar to let people go, but they hired a lot of people that they probably sho=
uldn=E2=80=99t have, and that payroll number had gotten very big. There=E2=
=80=99s been a
big shift in focus from investors and the market=E2=80=93=E2=80=93it used t=
o be on topline growth and growth at all costs, and now everybody wants pro=
fitability and EBITDA. Goop was very much in the growth-at-all-costs mental=
ity in the moment when the market was crazy. They built up this company bel=
ieving they were going to grow into this valuation, and people thought it w=
as going to be a unicorn quickly. You have to be as lean as you possibly ca=
n when you=E2=80=99re in this environment, and when the company is not
profitable. They=E2=80=99re close=E2=80=93=E2=80=93it=E2=80=99s not like it=
 was losing a lot more before.

